description.text: This is a basic character set built from the "FreeSans" font created by the FreeFont project (see http://www.gnu.org/software/freefont). I have had difficulty using the Wings3D "Text" function, because it only generates text that is free-standing in air. So I created a set of characters each in its own block, like typesetting blocks used for pinting presses. The set of files includes Wings3D and STL files of both extruded and intruded characters. Updated on 4/1/2014 to remove errors in edge orthogonality apparently due to roundoff error in one of the tools.

This character set was made for Wings3D, although of course it is possible to use with most 3D design programs.  With Wings3D, select the characters needed for a text string, and use the "Put On" function to attach each character to the one before it.  When the text string is complete, switch to "body" mode, select everything in the text string, and use the "Weld" function to combine all the text into a single object (you may need to use a tolerance much larger than the default, such as 0.01 instead of 0.001).  After welding, the lines between characters can be eliminated, and the text string can be welded onto any simple surface.  
The STL files can be imported into other tools like OpenSCAD, although manipulating the characters into text strings may not be as simple as it is in Wings3D.   
Because the FreeFont fonts are distributed by GNU under the GPL license, this character set has also been put under GPL.   Remember that many fonts are proprietary!  Read the page "why free fonts?" on the GNU FreeFont site for more detailed information.

title: TheKretchfoop's claw for printing without support

description.text:
The claw for TheKretchfoop's Clawshot, split along the midline and plated to make printing without support easier.  
This was posted by request.  Make sure you scale it to match the other parts you are printing. I believe that this is 50% of the original, but please verify.  
This was created in netfabb Basic 5.0 (free download) by opening the stl of the original part, adjusting the Z slider in the right hand pane to the desired cut position (or typing in the z-height), clicking Execute Cut, clicking Cut, expanding the part tree in the upper right hand view to show the now two separate parts, selecting the bottom part, clicking the rotate parts tool on the tool bar and rotating the bottom part 180 degrees about the X axis, clicking the move parts icon and moving the flipped part to position it beside and on the same Z-level as the other part, selecting both parts, and exporting them to a new stl file.  Hope it helps.
Be sure to scale it to match the other parts you are printing.

comments.text: Sounds great.  I only have a single extruder now on my Mendel 90.  Your Clawshot was one of the very first things I printed  when I built the printer last fall.  My son saw it and begged me to print it even though I thought it was a bit ambitious for a first print. I tried printing one claw with the raft and it was a mess.  I ended up repairing it and using it but the other two I split and printed which was much easier and saved a lot of plastic on a single extruder.  Our Clawshot turned out a bit rough (relative to later prints) since I was still learning how to use the printer but it is still awesome.  Thanks for all the effort that went into creating the model.
comments.author: neuport

comments.text: Awesome.  I just recently started printing these with Makerbot Dissolvable Support and ABS on my Rep2X, and I will say that it comes out beautifully.  I don't have to dissolve anytihng, the supports just peel right off and leave an amazing surface.  If you have a dual extruder, I highly recommend trying it.

remixed_from.title: Two-Blade Boomerang

description.text: A boomerang that I modeled after one that I made from wood. This is similar to thing:28603, it only has sharper airfoils and I took care that it is about 20 x 20 units in the STL file, which scales easily to the 20cm x 20cm space that the 3D printing company I use offers. Note for Lefties: You'll need a mirror image of the boomerang. A mirrored copy is included in the downloadable files.

Will work best if scaled to between 20 x 20 and 30 x 30 centimeters and a thickness of about 3.5 to 4.5 millimeters.  
Mine has a wingspan of 215 mm and is 3.5 mm thick.  
You can greatly enhance wind stability, spin retention, and distance by taping a small coin to the first arm as shown in the photo.
